transformations. In Shock Therapy Tomas Matza provides an ethnography of post-Soviet Saint Petersburg, following psychotherapists, psychologists, and their clients as they navigate the challenges of post-Soviet life. Juxtaposing personal growth and success seminars for elites with crisis counseling and remedial interventions for those on public assistance, Matza shows how profound inequalities are emerging in contemporary Russia in increasingly intimate ways as matters of selfhood. Extending anthropologies of neoliberalism and care in new directions, Matza offers a profound meditation on the interplay between ethics, therapy, and biopolitics, as well as a sensitive portrait of everyday caring practices in the face of the confounding promise of postsocialist democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic books. 0aPost-communismxSocial aspectszRussia (Federation). 0aPsychologistszRussia (Federation)zSaint Petersburg. 0aPsychologyzRussia (Federation)zSaint Petersburg. 0aPsychotherapistszRussia (Federation)zSaint Petersburg. 0aPsychotherapyzRussia (Federation)zSaint Petersburg. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822371953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822371953/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles